unity, the growth of political constituencies, academic administration and governance, and academic stratification by prestige. In closing, Smelser analyzes a number of contemporary trends and problems that are superimposed on the already-complex structures of higher education, such as the diminishing public support without alterations of governance and accountability, the increasing pattern of commercialization in higher education, the growth of distance-learning and for-profit institutions, and the spectacular growth of temporary and part-time faculty.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEducational changezUnited States. 0aUniversities and collegesxAdministrationzUnited States. 0aUniversities and collegeszUnited StatesxAdministration. 0aUniversities and collegeszUnited States. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh  aacademic administration.  aacademic community.  aacademic department.  aacademic disciplines.  aacademic freedom.  aacademic stratification.  aacademic.  aaccountability.  aclark kerr.  acomplex structures.  acontemporary trends.  aeducation history.  aeducation policy.  aeducation reform.  aeducation.  aengaging.  ahigher ed leadership.  ahigher education.  ahistory.  apart time faculty.  apolitical constituencies.  apublic support.  astructural accretion.  ateachers and faculty.  atheory of change.  auniversities.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052027581240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095525740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520955257423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520955257/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEB